{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507884"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2688"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2688"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.48,0.18,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57050"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2688"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42505"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17714"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57050"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of seven to eight episodes of bloody diarrhoea per day. He reports feeling fatigued and generally unwell. He has a medical history of ulcerative colitis and takes mesalazine suppositories. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft but tender in the left iliac fossa. After initial investigations have ruled out other diagnoses, he is diagnosed with an acute flare of ulcerative colitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would indicate severe ulcerative colitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 20 mm/hr (1-10)","Haemoglobin of 102 g/L (130-180)","C-reactive protein of 10 mg/L (\u003C5)","Platelet count of 200 x 10^9/L (150-400)","Pulse rate of 75/min (60-100)"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute severe ulcerative colitis (ASUC), which is a medical emergency requiring urgent inpatient care. ASUC is defined by the Truelove and Witts criteria: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMore than six bloody stools per day plus at least one of: \u003Cbr /\u003E- Pulse \u0026gt;90/min\u003Cbr /\u003E- Temperature \u0026gt;37.8\u00b0C\u003Cbr /\u003E- Haemoglobin \u0026lt;105 g/L\u003Cbr /\u003E- ESR \u0026gt;30 mm/hr.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemoglobin of 102 g/L\u003C/strong\u003E meets one of these criteria, indicating severe disease. This degree of anaemia suggests significant blood loss and mucosal inflammation, warranting urgent intervention with intravenous steroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythrocyte sedimentation rate of 20 mm/hr\u003C/strong\u003E would not meet criteria for severe disease, as the threshold is \u0026gt;30 mm/hr. ESR is a useful initial marker of inflammation but takes longer to rise and fall than CRP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein of 10 mg/L\u003C/strong\u003E, while elevated, is only mildly raised and would not indicate severe disease. CRP is useful for monitoring response to therapy as it changes more rapidly than ESR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eplatelet count of 200 x 10^9/L\u003C/strong\u003E is within normal limits and is not part of the severity criteria for UC. While thrombocytosis can occur in inflammatory states, it is not used to grade disease severity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epulse rate of 75/min\u003C/strong\u003E is within normal limits and would not meet criteria for severe disease, which requires a pulse \u0026gt;90/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of ASUC includes intravenous steroids as first-line therapy. If there is minimal response after 3-5 days, salvage therapy with infliximab or ciclosporin should be considered. Additional investigations should include stool cultures to exclude infection, abdominal X-ray to exclude toxic megacolon, and flexible sigmoidoscopy to assess disease extent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute severe ulcerative colitis (ASUC) is a complication of UC and is a medical emergency.","ASUC is defined by the Truelove and Witts criteria: \u003E6 bloody stools/day plus either pulse \u003E90/min, temperature \u003E37.8\u00b0C, haemoglobin \u003C105 g/L, or ESR \u003E30 mm/hr.","ASUC requires IV steroids and often salvage therapy with biologics."],"references":["Assasi N, Blackhouse G, Campbell K, et al. Comparative Value of Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR) and C-Reactive Protein (CRP) Testing in Combination Versus Individually for the Diagnosis of Undifferentiated Patients With Suspected Inflammatory Disease or Serious Infection: A Systematic Review and Economic Analysis [Online]. In: Ottawa (ON): Canadian Agency for Drugs and Technologies in Health; 2015. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK333366/","Kedia S, Ahuja V, Tandon R. Management of acute severe ulcerative colitis. World J Gastrointest Pathophysiol. 2014;5(4):579-588. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4231522/","Ulcerative Colitis. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd [online]. 2019. Available at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=inflammatory-bowel-disease\u0026guidelineName=Gastrointestinal#toc_d1e365.","Truelove SC, Witts LJ. Cortisone in ulcerative colitis; final report on a therapeutic trial. Br Med J. 1955;2(4947):1041-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/13260656/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42505"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2688"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42505"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T08:04:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T08:05:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2688"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57050"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":